@node roadiereview "Roadie Review"
@toc reviews
	   @{b}@{fg fill}*Roadie Review - February 2022*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
Roadie

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
TCP/IP stack RoadShow
Kickstart 2.0
68020+

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Commodore Amiga 4000
Amiga OS 3.2.1 

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Roadie the little helper for Roadshow!@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
I 'used' to have some issues running WHDLoad games or
certain demos or programs that didn't work properly if
my internet TCP/IP program (Roadshow) was working. So you say 
easy just 'close' Roadshow right or use custom WHDLoad script to disbale 
the TCP/IP stack right...ah that doesn't work all the time, at least not 
for me and my Amiga 4000 running OS3.2.1 and even when I did manage to 
shut down Roadshow successfully I still had to reset my Amiga to get it 
back up.

That was then BUT then a small program came out on aminet called Roadie 
that changed my TCP/IP stack woes! Roadie is simply a small GUI program
that allows you to turn off and turn on Roadshow with a mouse button 
click and it just simply 'works'! It also allows you to show your current 
net status i.e local IP, Gateway, DNS and to PING a given IP/Host all from 
AmigaOS.

Currently version 1.3.9 is available for download on aminet and requires 
kickstart 2.0 and a 68020 CPU as minimum requirements and of course 
Roadshow needs to be installed as well.

I was so happy with this little program that I reached out to the 
developer (Graham Thomson) to enquire about where I could send a donation 
to show my appreciation and he simply replied that he was happy that it 
would help other amigans and thanked me for my feedback....that's why I 
love Amiga and AmigaOS back in the 80's to today..simply our community was 
and still is always helpful and supportive :-)

Cheers.

@endnode

@node indivisionmk3review "Indivision AGA MK3 Review"
@toc reviews
 	    	  @{b}@{fg fill}*Indivision AGA MK3 Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
Indivision AGA MK3

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Available From@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
www.icomp.de/en/shop/product/Flickerfixer_Scandoubler.html 
190.56 euros

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Hardware Requirements@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Amiga 1200 or A4000T with a modification

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Commodore Amiga 1200
Classic WB + 3.2 Kickstart 

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Welcome To The Mk3@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
As most Amiga users are aware, connecting an Amiga to a monitor can be a 
bit tricky at times, especially with the lack of 15khz capable monitors 
available.  Composite frankly gives a terrible picture exaspurated by 
LCD/LED screentechnology.  Using the RGB port does wonders for display 
quality but many monitors now only have HDMI ports. The Indivision is 
one of the few cards to offer modern connections to monitors and TVs. 
There have been several iterations of the card going back to the original 
Indivision AGA, Indivision AGA Mk2, Indivision AGA Mk2Cr and the current 
Mk3.  Each version has added new features and corrected errors, and 
updated the video connector.  Is is also possible to upgrade the firmware
providing more features and stability.  We will have a look at the latest
firmware in a future issue. 

Purchasing the Mk3 is relatively easy, I had ordered directly from the
Individual Computers website since it did not seem to be listed on any
other Amiga reseller's page.  Ordering had not issues, I paid via bank
transfer, usually I do not do this but I have ordered in the past from
Jen's website and never had issues.  This is one of the nice things about
the Amiga scene, while there are scammers abundant, there are those like
Jen's who provide a truly professional and trustworthy experience.

After payment, I received my confirmation e-mails promptly and the card 
was sent out the next day, very fast processing!  Only a week later and
the Japan Post delivery man was ringing my door bell.  Upon opening the 
box I was struck by how small it looks and by the additional connector
for the keyboard.  The other major difference was the video connector 
having VGA and HDMI on the same board.  Thank you Jen's for putting both 
on the adapter, it makes using the card so much easier.  The board also 
now has a hole to screw it into the spare slot on the right side of the 
A1200 which previous versions did not have.  It was a bit stressful having 
the video cable hanging out of the Amiga unattached and the Mk3 version 
update is very welcome.

Prior versions of the board required you to connect the board to just the
Lisa chip, with the Mk3 there is an additional adapter that needs to be
connected to a CIA chip which sends keyboard signals to the Indivision.
Attaching the board is easy, you do need to press firmly down but once the 
card is attached it stays.  In prior versions the Indivision had issues 
with the board popping off.  This was fixed in the Mk2cr and it is good to 
see that the Mk3 also has a firm fit.  Once the main board has been attached
to the Lisa, you need to attach the keyboard board adapter.  This can be a 
little tricky since it is a very tight fit between the adapter. If you are
worried about the keyboard connector, it might possible to sandpaper down 
the side touching the keyboard connector.  All that is left is now to choose 
if you want HDMI or VGA.

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}In Use@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
For this review I used a Toshiba 1280x1280 monitor, the Amiga was 
connected via the VGA port.  As a precaution I had set my screenmode to 
PAL Hires before installing the flickerfixer just incase of trouble.  Upon 
first bootup I was greeted with a pin sharp image abeit a bit off centre.  
Colours were strong and there was no visible ghosting that you can get 
with other scandoublers.  The Indivision's settings can be adjusted from 
the IndivisionAGAmk3 tool. It is here you can set the output resolution 
for each of the screenmodes you are using.  This is a great jump over 
previous versions allowing you to get the best quality image even with 
multiple screenmodes.  Since I run my Workbench in different screenmodes 
with OctaMED, Brilliance, Lightwave and ProText this is particulary 
useful.  It takes time to find the resolution that will work with your 
monitor however had I fairly good luck with EDID resolutions which are the
compatible resolutions automatically detected by the Indvision.  You have 
many options in the tool such as adjusting the minimum and maximum lines,
'Advanced' will take you to another window where you can now route the
audio through the HDMI port, as my monitor does not have internal speakers
I was unable to test this feature.  In addition to the HDMI audio routing
you can also enable/adjust: DoubleBuffer, Powersave, VSync Line, Graffiti
Emulation.  DoubleBuffer reduces the tearing effect if VSync is not 
available with the selected Indivision screenmode, Graffiti Emulation is
more of use for ECS machines since it allows 256 colours out of 4096 
without any HAM artifacting.  Finally VSync Line allows you to adjust the
amount of latency between the Amiga and VGA, it should be set to the 
lowest value possible.  There are many more features that can be adjusted
via the software but this would become a very long review if I reviewed 
each feature.  To find out more details visit the icomp wiki page at: 
wiki.icomp.de/wiki/Indivision_AGA_MK3/doc

It pays off to have play around with the settings, in particular the VGA 
Mode, Test Mode and Test/Adjust button.  It is here that you can find out
which resolution best suits your monitor.  In general I found PAL Hires 
and NSTC Hires modes looked best with the Indivision, I also recommend 
trying the HighGFX modes which are available from Aminet.  When I use my 
Amiga with a widescreen monitor I find SUPERPLUS:Hi Res a nice compromise
between screen space and chipram.  However there are many different 
resolutions that are now open to you thanks to the Indivision that it 
makes sense to try them all first, everyone will have a different 
resolution that they prefer.

Regarding general use when switching between resolutions I noticed there 
is quite a delay, I am not sure if this is the Indivision or my monitor
taking time to sync with the different resolution.  As a rule of thumb
I try to keep the same VGA resolution for my Workbench, Hires and Hires
Laced screenmodes.  This covers most of the resolutions that I use in
Brilliance, Lightwave and OctaMED.  I could see no issues with the video
quality, there was some noticable distortion when the mouse moved in HiRes
Laced modes (PAL and NTSC) but it was not too distracting. 

Regarding games I have to confess to not having tried them, I was more 
concerned about seeing pixels properly when working in Brilliance.  It is
here where I find the Indivision becomes an essential purchase.  There are 
a variety of ways to connect your A1200 to monitors but none that I have 
used so far, gave me as clear and clean picture as the Indivision.  It is 
a pleasure to edit pixels with Jen's scandoubler and I think this is where 
the card really shines.
 
If you are looking for a pixel perfect display, where being able to see 
the individual pixels matter then the Indivision AGA Mk3 is the card for 
you.  

It is not a cheap card so if you are primarily using your Amiga for games 
the Indivision might be a bit of an overkill.  However if you are doing 
graphics, coding or writing on the Amiga then the Indivision AGA Mk3 is 
the best scandoubler on the market.  It has to stated though that the 
Amiga chipset is what it is, and that is 30 year old hardware that was not 
intended to run in high resolution and colour.  The Indivision at best is 
a way to enjoy the Amiga's native resolutions on a modern TV or monitor.  
It will not make a 256 colour screen run faster, but it will allow you to 
enjoy a 64 colour HiRes Laced screen without giving you headache.  
  
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Final Thoughts@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Getting your Amiga hooked up with decent picture quality has become more
troublesome as newer technologies become more standard.  There are a 
number of solutions but the Indivisions stand above the rest for providing
the best way to get a clear and clean image from your Amiga to a modern
monitor.  With the Mk3 Jen has addressed many of the issues that plagued
the earlier releases, the main one now having the both HDMI and VGA ports
on one adapter.  With the added keyboard dapter it is now also possilble 
to adjust the picture temporarily if your image is off centre or too 
small.  The IndivisionAGAMk3 tool is a very complex and useful beast, it
will take time to figure out how everything works but it will be time
well spent.  If you are looking for the best possible native Amiga output
then the Indivision AGA Mk3 should be your only choice. 

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Pros and Cons@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
+ Easy to install
+ Very well built
+ Has both HDMI and VGA ports
