@node pimiga2review "PiMiga 2.0 Review"
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*PiMiga 2.0 X64 Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
PiMiga 2.0 X64

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Chris Edwards YouTube Channel
http://bit.ly/3FVNiL4

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Special Hardware and Software Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Raspberry Pi4 or Pi400.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Machine Used For Testing@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Raspberry Pi400

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Review@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
PiMiga is an Amiga emulation environment for the Raspberry Pi series of 
computers, the current version is 2.0 and is recommended for the Pi4/400.  
The official website states "PiMiga 2.0 X64 - A Linux emulation system 
using Scalos WB replacement".  Created by the charasmatic
Chris Edwards it provides an Amiga experience the of which you could never 
have on real hardware or at least without breaking the bank.  When running
on a Pi400 it is 2,479 times faster than a stock A600, which in a word is 
awesome!

I have enjoyed using version 1.5 and was highly anticipating 2.0 which 
promises more speed and features such as additional controller
support, Zeb's EAB Whdload from October 2021, more music mods and the
ability to call BBS systems from the Internet.  Suffice I was very 
excited about this release.  I bought a Pi400 for the sole reason of
running PiMiga and to see Chris keeping it updated makes me feel much 
happier in my purchase.  What makes it even better is that he does not
ask a penny for his work, but welcomes contributions.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Installation@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
The image file can be found at http://bit.ly/3FVNiL4 - previously 1.5
came in at hefty 64gb and uncompressed to a 128gb image.  2.0 though has 
been on a diet and comes in at a more modest 22.1gb, expanding to 64gb.  
Chris has thoughtfully created a torrent of the file meaning those who do 
not have internet access all the time can download the file bit by bit.  
Once you have it downloaded, you will need to unpack it and then transfer 
the image to a MicroSD card.  For this you will need the Raspberry Pi 
Imager, it can be downloaded from http://www.raspberrypi.com/software/.

After downloadeding the imager, plug in your free SD card, load up the
Raspberry Pi Imager, and locate the PiMiga image, then write it to the
card.  It will take a little while so go have a cup of tea or get ready
for the next part.  When the card has been written two partitions will
appear on your desktop/devices, 'KICK' and 'boot'.  We are interested 
in 'KICK' for it is here that we need to copy the A1200 3.1 kickstart 
rom, it should be named 'kick31a1200.rom', copy this over then eject 
your card and insert it into the Pi400.  Upon first power up the monitor 
will display lines of text, you can ignore these as in a short while the 
PiMiga boot screen will popup followed by the ScalosWB desktop.  If you 
wish to access the internet or use bluetooth devices please have a look 
at the readme file found in the PiMiga download.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Now You Are Using Power!@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
I use a 21.5" I-O Data monitor for my A1200 and it has an HDMI port to 
plug in the Pi400.  The PiMiga desktop looks beautiful in 1080p, the icons 
are colourful and sharp.  From first glances it looks like the Amiga 
Workbench of my dreams.  Opening windows and applications are silky smooth 
and fast.  It does feel a bit more responsive compared to the previous 
release.  

Some minor but immediate changes are noticable such as the removal of the
changing background.  There is so much stuff to see and use in this 
package that there is not enough scope in this review to cover everything.  
I think this is part of the charm of PiMiga, there is such a electic 
selection of music, videos, images and software that it will take a long 
time to fully appreciate the depth of the work that must have gone into 
making PiMiga.  For the sake of this review I will cover a few points that 
I think most users will be interested in.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Browsers Galore@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
PiMiga comes with variety of web browsers, the most prominet ones being
NetSurf and AWeb on the Amiga Workbench screen.  I found NetSurf gave me
the most modern browsing experience but it did have a tendency to crash
or freeze, especially upon starting.  Aweb was very fast but did not 
render modern pages so well.  There are quite a few web browsers for the 
Amiga, it would be interesting to have them all installed if possible such 
as Timberwolf, having the ability to use a modern browser would make the
PiMiga more than just a curiosity.  Setting up an internet connection is 
easy but needs to be done from the Pi400 CLI.  Other networking software 
included are SMBMounter, WookieChat and YAM alongside other BBS and 
networking software.  When I ran IBrowse the Amiga emulation crashed and 
dumped me into the Pi CLI.  It seems not all software has been fully 
tested yet but PiMiga is constantly evolving and I am sure what bugs 
currently exist will be addressed in a future update.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Video On Your Amiga@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
This is something that I found quite enjoyable, being able to play videos
with ease on PiMiga is something that even my mightly A1200/060 could not
handle due to the AGA chipset limitation.  There are a lot of videos for
your viewing pleasure and it is a lot fun playing videos directly on your 
Workbench, it makes Workbench almost feel modern.  Now if we could only 
get YouTube to run in PiMiga, that would be very nice indeed.  One thing 
that I hope Chris will add in future versions are playable versions of his
YouTube videos, it would add a uniquely personal touch to PiMiga.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}All The Rest@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
There is so much content included in PiMiga 2.0, the WHDLoad set, various 
graphics software such as Lightwave 5, ImageFX 2 and OctaMED Studio.
Lightwave 5 did not want to load due to Toaster assigns, Lightwave 4 did 
not have this issue.  Being able to run software that requires an FPU is
very useful.  While my A1200 has an 060, it is not one with an FPU, full 
060 with FPUs are going for crazy prices so I doubt that I ever will.  

If you are looking for music then the Mods folder is chock full of audio 
pleasure, catering to all listening styles.  In this regard the PiMiga 
could become a pint sized Amiga music box.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Final Thoughts@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
It is obvious that a lot of work has gone into creating PiMiga and Chris
should be commended for creating such an expansive project and for not
stopping at version one.  There is so much content that runs the gamut of 
the Amiga spectrum that it can be a little overwhelming at first.  
Searching for a particular file or programme can be a little daunting,
there are so many drawers and paritions, making it hard to know where to 
start.  However properly exploring PiMiga will reward you with some truely 
unique Amiga experiences.

It is difficult to find fault with PiMiga, it alone makes purchasing a
Pi400 worth it.  However there are a few things that would make it a 
better product, the drawers and organisation of files are a bit haphazard
making it hard to find what you want.  Using a similar organisational 
format to that of ClassicWB would help in this area.  In addition windows 
do not always show all the contents, when opening a drawer you need to 
scroll down to find the application.  These are all small niggles and do 
not detract from the amazing work done by Chris, it is all the more 
amazing that he is giving this away for free.  

If you have a Pi400 and have not installed this yet, then what are you 
waiting for?!  Download it now and enjoy a modern Amiga experience in a 
form smaller than an A600.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
+ Easy to setup
+ Most powerful Amiga you will ever get for £60
+ Free
- Can be a bit difficult to find software, needs a bit of house cleaning

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Scores@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Ease Of Use: 90%
Documentation: 90%
Value For money: 100%
Overall: 94% - WhatIFF? Gold
@endnode
@node roadshowreview "Roadshow Review"
@toc reviews
		@{b}@{fg fill}*Roadshow Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
Roadshow Ver. 1.14 (14/09/2020)

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
www.amigashop.org (Full Version) 
www.roadshow.apc-tcp.de (Demo Version)

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Special Hardware and Software Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Any Amiga with a harddisk, ram expansion and network card: PCMCIA, Zorro 
or Plipbox 

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Machine Used For Testing@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Commodore Amiga 1200
KS/Workbench 3.2
Indivision MK3, TF1260

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Modern Internet On Your Amiga @{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
The Amiga has always had the ability to get online since the early days of 
BBSs and even when the Web was in its infancy.  There have been numerous 
TCP/IP programmes released for the Amiga over the years; AmiTCP, Miami, 
EasyNet and Genesis (Included with Amiga OS3.9).  All of these programmes
worked well on the Amiga but not many have been updated with modern 
features and at times struggle connecting to home networks.  In the past I
used Miami for connecting my towerised A1200 with a 603/040 + BVision
card, perfect for surfing websites in 24Bit colour.  However today I do 
not own that powerhouse of an Amiga and require something that can run on
lower spec hardware, enter Roadshow.  

The first thing that strikes you about Roadshow, is there is no GUI or 
visual interface.  Miami and EasyNet both have graphical user interfaces, 
taking some of the pain away from setup.  Roadshow has thrown away these 
aspects of the program, freezing up precious Chipram.  While this might 
make it a little harder for newcomers to setup a connection it has the 
added benefit of taking up a smaller footprint and gaining some very 
welcome speed.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Installation@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}      
Installation was quick and easy, it first asks you if you want to install 
versions of the Roadshow bdsocket.library and  PPP/PPoE drivers optimised 
for your system.  Obviously you will click 'Yes', the installer will ask 
you where you want to install the files and then will go and do its thing.  
It is a very fast and painless experience.  After it has finished 
installing you are are asked to reboot your Amiga.

Roadshow creates two new drawers in 'Devs' and 'Storage'- 'NetInterfaces'
and 'Networks', it is from here that you will be able to configure your 
internet connection.  The first file to look at is in 
'Storage -> NetInterfaces'.  Opening the drawer will present a list of
various network devices.  Choose the file that has the same name as your
network device or check on the internet for one that is closest to your
model.  When you find the file that corresponds with your device, it has
to be copied over to the 'Devs->NetInterfaces'.  The file needs to be 
edited and it here where you will configure device name, DHCP, Static 
IP Address, and NetMask.  Next you will need to edit the Routes file in 
the 'Devs->Internet' drawer.  Compared to the NetInterface file, Routes is 
quite simple to setup requiring just the router IP address.  The final 
file that needs editing is the 'Devs->Internet' name_resolution file.  All
you need here is to enter your ISP's DNS addresses. 
                                
Once you have saved the file edits the Amiga needs to be rebooted for the 
changes to take effect.  You will not notice any difference after booting, 
to check that your Amiga is connected to the internet, you will either 
need to load up a web browser or use the Ping command via the Shell.  I 
usually use my router address for the ping.

Coming from Miami, Roadshow had seemed a little daunting at first, but 
once I had practiced with changing the settings it became much easier.  It
is important to have the needed information ready and on hand such as your 
router IP address, whether you want to use DHCP or a static address and 
your ISP DNS addresses.  If you have these ready before installation the 
process of setting up Roadshow becomes much easier.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Roadshow In Use@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  
Roadshow by default has no tools to indicate the Amiga has successfully
connected to the network/Internet.  For this you need to load a web 
browser or start a ping.  It sits in the background quietly handling all
your network traffic.  I find this refreshing on the Amiga, previous TCP
software made you click on a connect button along with a connected timer.
This was useful during the times when we connected our computers
directly via modem but now with most households using a router, there is 
no need for these intrusive design elements.  Roadshow brings the Amiga 
into the present by providing an update and integrated  way of connecting 
your Amiga to the Internet without oudated and intrusive windows.

The software takes up very little ram and does not slow down my Amiga or
tax it in anyway.  At times I had forgot that I was connected to the 
Internet and it was a pleasure to realise all I had to do was open AWeb
and go to the website I needed.  There are a variety of commodities for
Roadshow that can be downloaded from Aminet, providing features such as
network monitoring and disconnect/connect buttons.  However for the 
moment I am quite happy having Roadshow sit in the backgound unnoticed.
   
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Final Thoughts@{uu}@{ub}@{fg text}
While there are a number of other TCP/IP solutions available for the
Amiga, MiamiDX is now available for free and AmigaKit sells EasyNet,
I find that I am leaning towards Roadshow.  Reason  being that while it
may not be as user friendly to set up as the aforementioned applications
it is faster, provides more modern features and sits in the background
quietly not calling attention to itself.  Setup can be be a bit confusing
for first time users but watch a YouTube video and you will quickly get
the hang of it.  The digital download is 25 euros which is about 10 euros
more than the asking price of 15 euros for the EasyNetPro CD.  Roadshow 
appears a little steep considering it is just a digital download but you 
get a more streamlined and modern piece of software.  For those who are 
not sure if Roadshow is for them, a 30 minute limited free demo can be 
downloaded, which I highly recommend.     
 
@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
+ Lightweight
+ Fast and supports modern connections
+ Has additional commodities
- Can be a little difficult for people who do not know about networks
- More expensive than the competition

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Scores@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Ease Of Use: 85%
Documentation: 90%
Value For money: 85%
Overall: 87% - WhatIFF? Silver
@endnode

