@node lightwave101 "Lightwave 101 - Mirroring And Welding Your Object"
@toc guides
                          @{b}@{fg fill}*Lightwave 101 - Part 2*@{ub}@{fg text}
                           Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Half A Ball@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Welcome back to the second installment of the Lightwave 101 tutorial 
series.  In the last issue we learned how create half a boing ball and how 
to assign colours to the facets/polygons.  Two things I need to note 
however, in the first tutorial I mentioned the Radii as being 1,000 for 
tutorial the number should be left at the default value.  Secondly 
create an assigned colour in Lightwave 3.5 is not possible from the 
Modeler, in newer versions it is  possible with in the modeler however in 
3.5 you need to go to Layout mode.  I will quickly cover how that can be
achieved below.

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Assigning Colours In The Layout@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Load your object by clicking on 'Objects' from the top menu and then 
'Load Object' in the window that pops up.  Find your half boing ball
and load it, once it is loaded click on 'Continue'.  To assign a colour we 
need to go to the 'Surfaces' button at the top.  Another
window will pop open and at the top you can see "Current Surface", next to
it the button should have 'Red' or 'White' written on it.  Let's presume 
it is Red first, click on 'Surface Color' and you will be presented with a
dialogue window showing three sliders for Red Green and Blue.  Since this
surface is titled Red lets move the Red slider all the way to the right so
the value is 255.  Green and Blue can be slid all the way to the left so 
the value is 0.  Click on 'OK', then left mouse click and hold on the
button that says 'Red', a pop up menu will appear with three options:
Default, White, Red, choose White and do the same as before.  Click on
'Surface Color' then set all three sliders to the right.  Click on 
'Continue' to get back to the main screen again.  To do a test render 
click on 'Render' at the bottom left hand of the screen.  This will not
save the image but you can see if the red and white have been assigned
correctly in the black and white preview image.  If it looks correct
press Esc to go back to the main screen.  We probably should save the
object now.   Click on 'Objects' at the top of the screen, under current
object click on 'Save Object', it will ask you if you want to overwrite
the current object, click 'OK'.  For the next stage in this guide
you will need to go back to the Modeler, you can click on Modeler in the
top left of the screen to jump back or if you are worried about Chipram
then quit and load the Modeler seperately. 


@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Let's Mirror That Ball!@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
For this second half of the guide it will be a little easier since all we
will do is mirror the object.  At the beginning of this project we had
created a ball with it's centre at (0,0,0), this means that if we make
a mirror of the current object we will get an equal and opposite 
hemisphere, perfect for continuing the checkerboard effect of a boing
ball.

To begin with we need to go to the 'Multiply' menu button at the top of the
screen.  Click on this and then the 'Mirror' button on the left side of
the screen.  The cursor will change to a mirror creation cursor, the 
mirror plane can be placed anywhere with this method however we want a
very specific location for the plane so we will use the Numeric tool 
instead.  Click on 'Numeric' and a dialogue box will pop up, this is the
same in in all versions of Lightwave, in this instace we want to click on 
the 'Y' Plane, 'Position' can left at 0, click on 'OK' once you have 
chosen 'Y' Plane.  You will see a yellow horizontal line appear in
the Face pane.  All you have to is click on the 'Make' button and the
ball will become a whole ball again.  We do not need this menu anymore, to
leave it click on one of the buttons at the top of the screen.

One problem that we have now is the bottom image is an exact mirror which
means at the equator we will have some elongated white rectangles, for
the boing ball effect to work the bottom half will have to be rotated by a
certain amount.  


@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Let's Spin This Ball@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
Before spinning the lower hemisphere we need to check that you are in 
Polygon mode, this can be set by clicking on 'Polygon' at the bottom of
the screen.  Using the Face pane, left mouse click on the lower half 
facets/polygons.  You will need to keep the left Shift key pressed while
doing this otherwise you will be unable to choose multiple facets.  Once 
you have done this it is time to rotate our lower hemisphere.  Click on 
'Modify' at the top of the the screen and then 'Rotate' from the left 
menu.  We want to be very specific with this.  After clicking on 'Rotate' 
click on 'Numeric' at the bottom left menu.  Under Axis click on 'Y', for 
the angle type in 22.5.  We want to rotate by one facet/polygon or 360/16 
degrees which is 22.5 degrees.  A 12x6 boing needs 30 degrees and a 
24 x 12 needs 15 degrees and so on.

Once you have rotated the lower hemisphere, do not worry if it looks the
same, we are only viewing it as a wireframe in black and white.  If it was
possible to preview in colour polygon mode you will would be able to see
the effect of the rotation.


@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}The Final Merge@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
Everything okay so far?  We are almost at the end of this second part, all 
we need to do now is merge or weld the object.  As it stands the two 
hemispheres are separate, if we were to render the object you might see a 
line between the seperate objects which is not our desired result.  
Previously we were working in Polygon mode but for this we will need to 
switch back to Point mode, which can be done from the bottom button 
'Point'.  

The points are what define the polygons.  There are 16 points for the top 
and bottom hemispheres, we want to make those 32 points into 16 points, it 
can be done with the Weld tool but you will need to select the points by 
hand and that takes time and can be fiddly.  A much faster and easier way 
is to use the Merge tool, found from 'Tools' at the top then 'Merge' from 
the left menu again.  Merge will automatically merge or weld any points 
that are occupying the same location.  Just make sure you select 
'Automatic' and then click on 'OK'.  A popup window will pop up saying 16
points eliminated.  Save your object and take a breather.  You will not 
notice any difference in the Modeler.  To  see if things have worked out
properly you will need to render the object from the Layout or Lightwave
program.  Good luck with your test render!  In the third part of this 
tutorial we will look at how to make your boing ball look smoother.  
See you next time!
 
@endnode  

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - How To Create A Perspective View"
@toc guides
		  @{b}@{fg fill}*Brilliance 101 - Part 2 Perspective*@{ub}@{fg text}
                           Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}A New Perspective@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Welcome back to our Brilliance 101 tutorials, in part one we learnt 
how to create a marble texture using the smear and blend tools.  In part 
two we will be using the checkerboard marble texture that you made 
previously.  Quite often you see this effect in images created on the 
Amiga and it is a very effective and useful effect to know about.

To start off, you will need to load your marble image and create a brush 
from it.  This can be done using the 'Cut Brush' tool, click and hold the
right mouse button and drag an outline around the marble.  Remeber to not
leave any space between the marble and the black background.  If you find
it difficult to do this then use the 'Magnify' tool to get in closer.

When you create a brush, the pointer will become your image, for
safe keeping lets put it into the brush board as I call it.  Right mouse
click on the 'Cut Brush' tool which looks like a pair of scissors, a new
tool box will open up with four squares, left mouse click in two of the 
boxes, a small thumbnail of your current brush will be displayed.  

Next we need to adjust the angle of perspective, with your brush still
chosen go to the 'Tweening' tool, it looks like three squares stacked on
top of each other.  Left click on the button and you will be presented 
with the Tweening options.  Look for the 'Adjust' button in the middle of 
the panel.  Once you have clicked on it the screen will change to black 
with a wireframe representation of your brush.  For this tutorial we will 
create a floor perspective so we want to change X Rot (Rotation), click on 
the X button and then move the cursor to the black screen, click and hold 
the left mouse button and move the mouse from right to left, the wireframe 
willrotate accordingly.  For this image let's set the X Rot at 77.  Once 
you have it there click on 'Use', you will then be taken back to the main 
edit screen.  For the moment you will not see any change in the brush, we 
need to use two tools to create a perspective.

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}Perspective Fill@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
First thing we need to do is left mouse click on the 'Fill' tool which 
looks like a typical paint tin.  We need set up the perspective, so right 
mouse click on the 'Draw Mode' tool, it is located at the far right of the 
screen and looks like smudged paint.  Another tool bar will open up and 
from here you want to click on 'Perspective' on the left side of the 
screen.  Press the space bar to hide the tool bars and then click anywhere
in the black screen, you will see from the top of the screen the 
perspective fill slowly crawl down the screen.  If you had not hidden the 
tool bar you can view the fill countdown on the right side of the
screen.  Wait a little while and soon you will have a nice perspective 
fill.  The 'Tweening' tool is very powerful and if you have a chance to 
experiment with its various settings you can get some amazing effects. For
now save your image because next we will work on how to create a 
reflection of an object on your marble floor.

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}Additional Thoughts @{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
One final note is that if you are not happy with the perspective fill, i.e
it is a bit too pixelated creating a bigger brush will help with this.
Usually I try to create as large a brush as I can to keep as much detail
as possible when using the perspective fill.  Well that is it for this 
time see you in issue four where we will look into creating a reflected
object for your scene.  As usual you can view the sample picture in the
images drawer.  I hope to get the images to link within AmigaGuide but 
have run into issues with so I am sticking with a drawer for the example
images at the moment.  See you in issue four!
  
@endnode           		   

@node internetclock "Setting up an Internet clock on your Amiga"
@toc guides
    @{b}@{fg fill}*How To Setup An Internet Time Syncing Vlient*@{ub}@{fg text}
                       Written by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}

@{b}So why would you need to use an internet time syncing client anyway?@{ub}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Do you:@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}

- not have an RTC(real time clock) chip on your MB or accelerator board

- like to have your saved files date/time stamped

- have an RTC chip but notice sometimes the time is slighlty off from the 
  actual time

- have a hardware defect in your RTC chip that won't allow your Amiga to 
  save date/time properly after shutting down your Amiga

- don't like taking apart your Amiga every few years to replace a dead 
  RTC battery

If one or more of the situations above sound familair to you and you have 
your Amiga setup online then an internet time syncing client will be 
useful for you.  A simple to use internet time sync client that I use can 
be found on aminet.net as sntp.lha by Patrik Axelsson. This simple to use 
and setup client can sync both the system time and RTC against a SNTP or 
MTP server using the Simple Network Time Protocol.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}How do you set it up?@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}

- copy file sntp to the c: folder

- open your favourite text editor to  modify the startup-sequence file by
  adding the line 'c:sntp pool.ntp.org' (without the ''). This new line 
  needs to be placed above/before the 'LoadWB' line 

- ensure you have the correct country selected in Sys/Prefs/Local and 
  click Save

After the above two steps are completed you can rest assure that everytime 
your Amiga boots up it will always have the correct date and time.

Cheers.

@endnode

@node octameddcommand "How apply the D command effect in OctaMED"
@toc guides
            @{b}@{fg fill}*OctaMED 101 - The D Command*@{ub}@{fg text}
                      Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}What Is The D Command?@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub}
For this tutorial we will be looking at the D command.  For some reason I
have not seen this command mentioned in the OctaMED manual so I am not
what is it's proper name.  However when I have used the command previously
I noticed it recreated the effect used in some oldskool rave tracks.  If
applied to a vocal, it will make the vocal turn on and off very quickly.
While this can be done with the volume command we covered in issue 1, the
'D' command creates a much smoother and faster effect.  The song title 
escapes me at the moment but there is a track from around 1992 that uses
a vocal sample saying "Feel the pressure", the effect they use on this 
vocal is very reminiscent of OctaMED's 'D' command.  So how can we use 
this in OctaMED?

@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}How To Use D Command@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub} 
The 'D' command is a very simple and easy command to use, it first should 
be used with a relatively long sample or looped one to be more effective.
Choose your sample and place in the channel of your choose, so if your
sample is the first one it should look like this:
			
			000 D-3 10000

The first line is 000 the sample note is D-3 and 1 is the sample number, 
the remaining four 0s have no effect yet, hence they are 0.  To add the
'D' command all we do is place the 'D' in the middle of the right column.
It should loook something like this:

			000 D-3 10D00 		

If you were to play the block, you wouuld hear no difference, what we need
to do is add an activator.  For this instance I will use a higher number so
the effect will be more prominent.  To do this just add the number 9 into 
the right column, like this:

			000 D-3 10D09	
			001  |  10D09
                        002  |  10D09
                        003  |  10D09
                        004  |  10D09
                        005  |  10D09
                        006  |  10D09
                        008  |  10D09

Now if you play the block you will notice the 'D' command having its 
effect, you can change the effect by reducing the numbers in the right
column.  However going over 9 does seems to lose the effect of the 
command.  Have a play around with this command and you can create some
fun effects for your tracks.  As a side note, I was unable to find the
name of this command but if someone out there knows where it is written
about please contact me so I can update this tutorial.  Have fun with
your OctaMED music making and next time we will have a look at the 
sequencing of blocks, to make a full song.

@endnode               

@node amigaspeak "Welcome to voices of the people behind Amiga hardware and software."
@toc contents
               	       @{fg shine}-= Amiga People - gwEm =-@{fg text}

 - = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = -
 
For issue 3 we are talking to Dr Gareth Morris a.k.a gwEm, a chip musician
who has played around the world and has a large backlog of music spanning
various genres.  Recently he released an album done soley on an Amiga, we
talk to him about his music history and the album.

 - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

@{b}1. Hello Gareth, thank you for taking the time for this interview, to 
start off can you introduce yourself, what you do and where you come from?@{ub}

@I am Dr Gareth Morris, artist name gwEm. My day job is as an electronics 
engineer, and in my spare time I am a serious chip musician. I have lived 
in Hackney, London, UK for a really long time now!

@{b}2.  Thank you for that Gareth, can you tell us what got you first into 
chip music, what was the first computer you used to make computer music?@{ub}

I got into chip music properly in 2001, producing something at least a bit 
respectable and performing live. Before this I was a semi-pro drum&bass DJ 
for a few years. 

There was a specific album, Maxi German Rave Blast Hits 3 from a group 
called Bodenstandig 2000 which got me into the scene. I liked this album 
so much that I contacted one of the members Drx, who gave me a diskette 
containing his favourite tracker MusicMon2.

I did make tracker music when I was kid in the 1990s, but it wasn't very 
good! Back then I used TCB Tracker on my Atari ST and later Fast Tracker 
2 on PC.

@{b}3. Your styles are quite eclectic ranging from drum'n'bass to punk to 
heavy metal to happy hardcore.  Is there a particular style or genre of 
music that you prefer to write and listen to?@{ub}

I listen to a lot of heavy metal, that is for sure. In particular I'm into 
Judas Priest, Mercyful Fate and certain power and symphonic metal bands. 
Punk is fun because its easy to play, and suits my limited vocal 
techniques :)

The other music I listen to a lot is old skool breakbeat rave.
When I go to party, its usually drum'n'bass or electro.

But I have a soft spot for happy hardcore, hip hop, classical, jazz, 
krautrock and other kinds of music.

If the music is melodic, energetic, and/or a little bit aggressive and 
abrasive, I'm there for it! 

I don't want to be tied into making one style of music only.

@{b}4. You wrote the software maxYMiser for the Atari ST can you explain a 
little about the software, what is it and why you made it?@{ub}

maxYMiser is a chip tracker for the Atari ST. I wrote it because I wasn't 
satisfied with the trackers available for Atari ST in the early 2000s. SID 
Sound Designer and MusicMon 2 were the predominant trackers, but neither 
of them included all the techniques that were possible on the YM2149 sound 
chip.

I still keep it up to date with the latest ideas, and bug fixes. As a 
result it is the longest maintained tracker on the Atari ST, and also the 
most popular.

@{b}5. The Atari ST is where you started making music, however recently you 
released a Breakbeat Hardcore album created solely on an Amiga 600, why 
did you choose the Amiga for this project?@{ub}

Of course, back in the 90s, there was a big rivalry between the Commodore 
Amiga and the Atari ST. Itâs very welcome now that the platforms are on 
friendly terms, although of course the Amiga scene is larger. Some Amiga 
musicians, like Mygg have even begun composing for the ST.

I used Protracker on a real Amiga a couple of times in the past, with 
friends, and found the workflow very fast and clean. Additionally, my 
favourite record label Slammin Vinyl produced all their classics 
using Amigas too. And we can name others: Meng Syndicate, Bizzy B etc etc.

Wanting to make new music with less of a chiptune sound, but with a 
tracker and staying true to my 16bit roots, the choice was clear.

@{b}6. What drove you to choose an A600 over, an A500 or A1200?@{ub}

Mostly the form factor.  In fact, the album was started on an A500 donated 
by a fan. Once I saw the Amiga was going to work out for me, I upgraded 
from the A500 to an A600. I don't really have interest in the A1200, but 
you never know!

The A600 has a smaller size, and 'modern' conveniences like compact flash. 
I made an audio modification recommended to me by Hoffman and I like the 
clearer sound of my modded A600 more than the A500 as well!

That first A500 I have gifted to friend 2xAA here in London, to try and 
keep the love going. It seemed like the right thing to do.

@{b}7. How does the music process differ from the Atari and Amiga?@{ub}

There are more similarities than differences I would say, since I use 
trackers on both.  Atari is much more technical. The YM2149 is weaker than 
the Paula, so you have to use a lot of tricks and techniques to make it sound 
good.

It's useful having sample music skills when composing on Amiga. Things like 
tuning samples is never a problem on Atari.  maxYMiser clearly has more 
features than Protracker and things like blocks, cut and paste etc goes 
quicker.

But overall, since I am tweaking the sound less on Amiga, I would say the 
Amiga is faster to get things done.

@{b}8. What problems did you encounter or what things went better than you 
expected when writing the album?@{ub}

Solutions to a lot of common Amiga issues are present on the internet. So 
I spent some time reading on Amiga message boards.

Initially, I had to spend a few weeks working on the Open Amiga Sampler 
(from Mnstrmnch and Syphus). I tried a Techno Sound Turbo at first, but it 
didn't sound good. I've kept the TST as a curiosity. 

The OAS was immediately better, but I could tell there was some more 
potential to be unlocked. I fixed a DC offset issue on the input stage, 
and used a SPICE program to design an adjustable anti-alias filter. 
Finally I made some changes to the first gain stage.

The DSS8 has a great reputation, but is much too expensive second hand due 
to collectors. I must tip my hat to the OAS project, as it is now possible 
for anyone to make a good quality Amiga sampling cartridge.

Generally it all went quite smoothly once the pieces were in place. Amiga 
is a very friendly machine to use.

@{b}9. When getting the samples into the Amiga did you sample them or 
convert them from a PC and why?@{ub}

Every sound on the album was sampled directly into the Amiga using my 
modded Open Amiga Sampler.  Many of my friends who are big Amiga composers 
like Interphace, Hoffman and Ctrix convert samples from PC. Clearly they 
all make awesome music, so that works for them. 

But I wanted a faster workflow, and I wanted to be hands on with my old 
synths. So I work exclusively with a sampler cartridge.

On Atari though, I work with an emulator. I do believe any method which 
lets you get the job done is the right way!

@{b}10. Which tracker do you prefer to use on the Amiga?@{ub}

I want to get into OctaMED, but honestly I use and prefer Protracker 
currently. It looks pretty and it's very comfortable. The latest version 
on 16-bits.org, with 128K samples is what I use.

@{b}11. What is your process when making a track?@{ub}

Often I will start with drums, but it's also possible I will start with 
chords, or a particular synth sound I like. Other times I will hear a 
track I like, and get inspired by that. In the rarest case, I will start a 
track by writing lyrics.

But one idea is never enough for a track, so I like to have at least two 
or three.

I'll build up a few patterns, and then figure out some transitions. At 
this point the track is nearly done.

I work with some particular vintage synths I like the sound of. On the 
Breaking Even release, I mostly used the Roland MC-202 since it sits next 
to my A600 so nicely. But I also featured the TB-303, U-220 and Korg 
Radias.

Another source of sounds is vintage sample CDs, such as the Datafile, 
X-Static Goldmine etc. I play them into the Amiga using a Pioneer CDJ.

All sample editing is done on the Amiga, although I may EQ the samples on 
a Mackie desk as I sample them.

The final mixes are all recorded from the back of the Amiga, with a tiny 
bit of tweaking on the Mackie desk. I also used a spring reverb unit. A PC 
was only used for uploading to the internet :)

@{b}12. Do you have any plans for more Amiga releases?@{ub}

Yes, and I am working on something right now. As soon as this interview is 
finished, I am going to get back to it :)

@{b}13. Finally are there any chip musicians that you recommend for our 
readers to listen to?@{ub}

From the Atari ST scene, I would recommend the composers 505 
(https://soundcloud.com/five-o-five) and Dma-Sc (http://dma-sc.atari.org).

From the wider chipmusic scene, some favourites are 
Cyanide Dansen (https://cyanidedansen.bandcamp.com) 
Breakbeat Heartbeat (https://breakbeatheartbeat.bandcamp.com).

@{b}Thank you Gareth for taking the time to answer these questions, I greatly 
enjoyed your album and have been listening to more of your music.  Keep up 
the awesome work!@{ub}  

Thanks a lot! I will keep going :)

@endnode
